03657nam a22005655i 9780226488257DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264882577 a10.7208/97802264882572doi  a(DE-B1597)521340  a(OCoLC)1118470838  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aB3317 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a1932231 aLampert, Laurence, eauthor.10aWhat a Philosopher Is :bBecoming Nietzsche /cLaurence Lampert. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart 1. Young Nietzsche in the Service of Schopenhauer and Wagner -- tPart 2. A New Public Nietzsche: Enlightenment Optimist -- tPart 3. Nietzsche Enters His Mature Philosophy -- tConclusion. The Philosophy and Art of Nietzsche's Maturity -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe trajectory of Friedrich Nietzsche's thought has long presented a difficulty for the study of his philosophy. How did the young Nietzsche-classicist and ardent advocate of Wagner's cultural renewal-become the philosopher of Will to Power and the Eternal Return?   With this book, Laurence Lampert answers that question. He does so through his trademark technique of close readings of key works in Nietzsche's journey to philosophy: The Birth of Tragedy, Schopenhauer as Educator, Richard Wagner in Bayreuth, Human All Too Human, and "Sanctus Januarius," the final book of the 1882 Gay Science. Relying partly on how Nietzsche himself characterized his books in his many autobiographical guides to the trajectory of his thought, Lampert sets each in the context of Nietzsche's writings as a whole, and looks at how they individually treat the question of what a philosopher is. Indispensable to his conclusions are the workbooks in which Nietzsche first recorded his advances, especially the 1881 workbook which shows him gradually gaining insights into the two foundations of his mature thinking. The result is the most complete picture we've had yet of the philosopher's development, one that gives us a Promethean Nietzsche, gaining knowledge even as he was expanding his thought to create new worlds.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aPhilosophy. 4aNietzsche's Nachlass. 4aNietzsche's development. 4aartist. 4aautobiography. 4aeternal return. 4aphilosopher. 4awill to power. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226488257423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226488257.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles